What is TDD?

ðï¸ A design technique.

ð A guided evolution.

ð§ª Write tests first.

  • It a technique in which tests help us designing our code, itâs not about testing.
  • It is a guided evolution with clear feedback after each step.
  • And last, but not least, itâs a process where we write tests before we write the production code.

3 steps of TDD

â Green

ð Refactor

3 steps of TDD

â Red

Write a failing test first. âï¸

â Green

ð Refactor

Red - this is the first step. We write a failing test. It will fail because the code we want to test doesnât exist yet. It will fail as long as we donât solve the problem we stated in the test.

This approach is the other way around to the test-last approach where we write tests to make them pass. In TDD we donât try to prove that the code we wrote works as expected. We write code to prove that it works as stated in tests.

3 steps of TDD

â Red

â Green

Write the production code.

Only as much as needed to make tests pass. â

ð Refactor

  1. Green - once we have at least one failing test, we can write production code to satisfy them.

Since we have the tests, we can run them as often as we need. We have a reporoducible way to check if the code works as expected. We donât need to setup the environment by hand or do a lot of clicking in the app.

If the code does what we want it to, the tests will pass.

  1. We write only as much production code as needed to make the tests pass. Why would we write more, if tests already pass? You Ainât Gonna Need It.

3 steps of TDD

â Red

â Green

ð Refactor

Donât worry about breaking things.

Make code more readable and maintainable. ð

  1. Refactor - Were you ever afraid of refactoring your code because you were afraid of breaking it? In TDD we donât have this problem. We have tests that ensure that the code works as expected.

  2. We donât only want to have working code, we want to have good code. One that is maintainable and readable. We can spend some time in this step to make sure our code is clean and easy to understand.

  1. Itâs useful to remember that each test consists of three parts:
  • Setup
  • Execution
  • Assertion

We can use #Arrange, #Act, #Assert comments to split our tests into those distinct parts.

  1. We start with the setup.

#Arrange is where we prepare the environment. This is where we need to figure out the inputs we need to solve the problem.

Why this is great? At this stage, we still focus on what we need to be able to solve the problem. Not how we will solve it.

Without understanding the problem we wonât be able write down the test. And this is good, we wonât write any production code until we have the understanding of the problem. This helps us mitigate the risk of implementing the wrong solution.

  1. #Act is where we call our code.

TDD gives us the freedom to experiment with interfaces.

We can try out a few different approaches even before we start writing the production code, possibly saving a lot of time on refactoring.

The test you write is the first user of your code. The way you call your code from tests is the way you want to call it from the production code. So, think about how you want to use your code before you write it.

This approach helps you make your functions and objects simple, no redundant parametrization or options.

At this point itâs difficult to make code more complex. We focus on getting the job done, not overengineering and future-proofing.

  1. In #Assert we focus on how to observe that the code works as expected.

Again, we wonât be able to do it without understanding the problem. We donât start writing production code until we know what we want to achieve.

In TDD we first define inputs and outputs, treating the not-yet-existing code as a black box that we will add later.

This approach produces tests that donât test implementation details. Itâs impossible to do so since there is no implementation yet!

This ensures we focus on behavior of the code in our test.

How do we use it for more complex problems?

2 approaches

ð Bottom-up

ð Top-down

2 approaches

ð Bottom-up

Start small. ð§±

Use existing pieces of codebase. ð§©

A design emerges. ðï¸

ð Top-down

2 approaches

ð Bottom-up

ð Top-down

List high-level objectives first. ð¯

Describe behavior from user perspective. ð

Fill in the gaps until tests pass. ð§±

  1. We focus on high-level objectives first.
  2. We describe the behavior from the user perspective. If itâs a Shiny app, this is the perspective of the user interacting with the app. If itâs a package, this is a perspective of the user using the functions exported from the package.

ðï¸ Do what helps you move fast.

Different problems may require different approaches.

ð§ª Use tests as the driving force.

They tell you if your code does what you think it does.

  1. We start from setting up the environment. We create a Shiny app from the module.
  2. Then we create an object that represents the module, it will be a proxy for communicating with the module.
  3. We donât do anything in the execution part. We first focus on the default behavior, when no actions were taken.
  4. We assert that the summary is visible.

Notice how we used a nonexistent DatasetSummary object. We will create it in the next step. For now our only focus is to imagine how we want to use it. We provide human-readable methods that will hide implementation details. This will make tests easier to understand and maintain.

Instead of using an object those could be functions. This doesnât matter, do what you feel is more natural to you. The important part is that weâre abstracting the actions we can take on the module.

Now we may realize, that we need data to show the summary. We can provide it through a data provider object. This could be an existing object in the app, or if weâre starting a new app, this can be a fake object that represents a way of getting the data. This way we can test the module in isolation. Without the access to the real data. What matters is the interface, we can always swap the implementation much easier than to change the interface.

So this data provider just serves the iris dataset via itâs get_summary method. The module doesnât need to know how the data is provided, it just needs to know how to get it. It could be from disk, from a database, it doesnât matter here.

DatasetSummary <- R6::R6Class(
  classname = "DatasetSummary",
  public = list(
    driver = NULL,
    selenider = NULL,
    initialize = function(app) {
      self$driver <- AppDriver$new(app)
      self$selenider <- selenider_session(
        driver = self$driver,
        local = FALSE
      )
    },
    expect_summary_visible = function() {
      find_element(self$selenider, css = "#summary > table") |>
        elem_expect(is_visible) |>
        elem_expect(\(x) has_at_least(elem_children(x), 1))
    }
  )
)

Next we can write focus on the assertion.

Think for a moment what outcome means that you met your objective.

In this case, asserting that the table is visible and that it has at least one row is a good way to ensure that the summary is shown.

Notice how this assertion is in a method. This way we can reuse it in other test cases. If at any point in time, our undestanding changes, we can change the implementation of this method, and all the tests will be updated.

Pay attention to names. They should be abstract.

â Green

dataset_summary.R
dataset_summary_ui <- function(id) {
  ns <- NS(id)
  fluidPage(
    tableOutput(ns("summary"))
  )
}

dataset_summary_server <- function(id, data_provider) {
  moduleServer(id, function(input, output, session) {
    output$summary <- renderTable({
      data_provider$get_summary()
    })
  })
}

DatasetSummary <- R6::R6Class(
  classname = "DatasetSummary",
  public = list(
    driver = NULL,
    selenider = NULL,
    initialize = function(app) {
      self$driver <- AppDriver$new(app)
      self$selenider <- selenider_session(
        driver = self$driver,
        local = FALSE
      )
    },
    expect_summary_visible = function() {
      find_element(self$selenider, css = "#summary > table") |>
        elem_expect(is_visible) |>
        elem_expect(\(x) has_at_least(elem_children(x), 1))
    }
  )
)

Why use TDD?

ðï¸ Faster development cycles.

ð§  Understanding the problem.

  1. Iâve worked with a legacy app that was not only a huge codebase, but it was also slow.

Each change took a lot of time to introduce. I had to run the whole app to see if the change I made worked as expected. I was lucky if the change was in the part of the app that was easy to reach, if it wasnât the case, the process was time-consuming and frustrating.

I had to ask myself a question: âIs there a better way to do this?â

  1. The other time I had to implement a feature that just by talking to a business expert I wasnât able to understand. I had to ask a lot of questions, and even then I wasnât sure if I understood the problem correctly.
  • Test give us entry points to the codebase, helping us move fast.

Conclusions - WIP ð§

  • Tests donât need to be a chore or an afterthought. They can be an integral part of development.
  • TDD itâs not about having a lot of tests. Itâs about tests that help you work faster and easier with the code.
  • Itâs about tests that tell you what the code does, not how it does it.
